<br>
I think it will be legal. The PST is close if you hit the sweet spot. I have a c405 DeMarini Classic that is close. The SB34 Genny I sold was close. I've heard the Rockettech (when broken in) is close. The difference in my opinion is the sweetspot size, so you get more of the "good" hits with the U2. <br>
<br>
Another factor, We all assume all these other bats are right on the bpf 1.2 mark, which could be false. They might be 1.1 or 1.0, which would allow the U2 to be slightly better and still be 1.2. For example, if the red shell PST was right at BPF 1.2, then how could it be improved with the Vanadium or the 137?? If the ESTs are right at 1.2, then why buy a Wicked or PST? Every bat maker says they "improve" their bats just about every year. How do they do that and stay under 1.2? It's probably because they are inching up from 1.0 to 1.05 to 1.1, etc. Miken may never be able to improve its bat, but because of durability you will still have to buy one every year or so. Some guys will break or buy 5 or 6 a year because they have the cash and they want the performance. It's a different marketing concept.<br>
<br>
It's funny how hype works. First it established the bat as "the" bat to have. Now it's working negatively to say the bat is too hot. I think the truth is somewhere in the middle. <br>
<br>
In my best Forrest Gump voice, "that's all I have to say about that."<br>
